Mesure_Dimensions:
Interior, from R.02 entrance:
W-1.98 x N-2.24 x E-1.98 x S-2.24

Wall widths:
0.61, 0.66, 0.50, 1.09
Description_General:
Alcove in north-side of room above the flue of the furnace Boon supposes there was a water tank.

Foundations are strongly reveted.
Description_Floor: Floor suspended above hypocaust with no ledge. No evidence of the mosaic remained, but its presence is supposed as R.02 had evidence for one.
Description_Notes: No longer extant and sits under the pavement and road.

Mesure_Dimensions: Width of 6.71m with a depth of 4.35m that breaks into an apse with a radius of 2.86m
Description_Purpose: TEPIDARIUM: the warm room in a Roman baths.
Description_General: Bathers first assembled here before moving onto other rooms. Usualy a clerestory window would be high on the wall lighting the space.
Description_Ceiling:
Likely a barral vault as these are typical for tepidarium. Tufa blocks appear to have been used to construct this. 

These blocks measured arround 0.230 x 0.140 x 0.065, but were broken.
Description_Floor:
Hypocaust very well built and simmilar to that of R.01. The mosaic floor was supported by 11 pilae each made simmilarly to R.01 and set close to walls to remove need for ledge to support floor.

Flue tiles were attached to the apse (four impressions remained at excavation)

Mosaic flooring evidenced through finds of tessarea cubes. Simmilar colours to R.03 and R.04
Description_Notes: The threshold of R.04 appears to have once been at the entrence of R.02.

Interior, from entrance to R.04:
W-0.86 x 2.32 x N-1.49 x E-3.03 x S-1.73

Bath:
1.50 x 0.65m
Description_General: Cold plunge bath (1.50 x 0.65m) set into floor with flagstone base. A drain runs under this and flows out the side of the building.
Description_Floor: Mosaic of a mat of guilloche bordered by a band of white. The colours of the guilloche are as in R.04.

Mesure_Dimensions:
Interior, from entrance to R.05
W-1.20 x 1.75 x N-1.95 x E-2.35 x 0.90 x S-1.85 x W-0.35
Description_Floor:
Mosaic pavement measuring 1.720 x 1.140 set within a margin of grey-green Pennant Sandstone cubes (2.54cm tessera). On three sides this is 0.230-0.380m wide, but to the west it is 1.140 wide.

The quatrefoils are in the same colours as those in the mosaic of R.07, and the guilloche is similarly coloured.

Boon suggests a bench was probably placed on the west boarder for changing as this is the wider boarder

W-1.09 x 1.95 x S-1.33 x E-3.20 x N-1.15 x W-0.20
Description_Purpose: Unclear, Boon proposes the intent was to create a latrine or a new room for a cold bath.
Description_General:
Boon describes this as having been ruinous with rubble being found in the centre of the room contemporanious with occupation. 

This rubble gradualy slopes away to mee the ground surface.

Description_Floor:
A fragment only remained of this pavement, in its s.w. corner. From pieces recovered from the hypocaust cavity, it may be said that the pavement resembled that of Room IV. 

Cubes for the pavements were knapped on the site. A primary period knapping floor, supplying tesserae for the mosaics of the west wing, was found at the west end of the porticus at the bottom of the infilling, and a secondary period knapping floor was found under the flags of Room V, for the mosaics of Rooms III and IV, and possibly for Room XI also.
